result.execSummary:
The defendant Andrew R. Holcombe was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manuf/Deliver Synthetic Cannabinoids(<=200g) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(em).
  • Manufacture/Deliver Non-Narcotics [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(b).
  • Manuf/Deliver Synthetic Cannabinoids(<=200g), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(em).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superMiscConds.notes: Court orders the fines, costs, and restitution in this file shall be paid from all funds received into the defendant's prison accounts in accordance with prison policy, not to exceed 25% of gross during the term of initial confinement. If any fines, costs, and/or restitution remain outstanding at the end of the initial confinement portion of this sentence, then the remaining shall be paid as a condition of extended supervision.

The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars, and is prohibited from ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician.  Defendant is prohibited from having any contact with N. Schubert.  Defendant is not to possess any chemicals or materials used in the manufacture of synthetic cannabinoids.
Defendant to undergo an alcohol and other drug assessment and comply with any further counseling and/or treatment as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.

Cases Called @ 11:12 AM: Defendant Andrew R. Holcombe in court with attorney Matthew Loren Goldin.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Global Resolution recited by DA.   DA speaks as to asset forfeiture which remains contested.  State will argue for forfeiture of those funds and Def will not be represented by Counsel.  Previous default was reopened due to communication not properly filed by Def.  Global resolution recited by DA with Joint agreement on resolution with brief argument on Time Served credit to be applied to cases.  14CF-176:  Court entertains waiver of pre-lim hearing.  Court accepts knowing and voluntary waiver of pre-lim hearing.  Def BOT.  INFO filed.  Receipt Admitted - Reading Waived.  Pleas confirmed to Cts 1, 4 and 5.  Defendant advised of minimum/maximum penalty for each count.  Terms of bifurcated SEH explained w/maximum terms of confinement and ES recited.  Advises Def of PTAC Enhancer. Plea QN reviewed w/Defendant.  Plea colloquy entertained.  Collateral consequences explained. Chapter 950 compliance addressed.  Plea Ct 1 (w/PTAC)  NC  Plea Ct 4 (w/PTAC):  NC  Plea Ct 5:  NC  Court accepts pleas and enters JOC.  Ct Nos 2 and 3 of 14CF-176 DRI.  Argument by Atty Goldin as to SEHR cases and application of TS credit.  Agrees w/Agent's recommendation w/concurrent terms to one another.  Argues for 123 time served credit apply to all cases - relationship of new case and SEHR cases.  Statement by Def:  Yes.  The Court:  Appropriate to follow agreement reached by Counsel - logical structure to it.  14CF-176:  Ct 1 - 36 mos bifurcated SEH - 18 mos IC/18 mos ES.  Ct 4:  5 yr bifurcated SEH - 2 yrs IC/3 yrs ES.  Ct 5:  36 mos bifurcated SEH - 18 mos IC/18 mos ES.  12CF-120:  4 yr term of imprisonment bifurcated SEH - 2 yrs IC/2 yrs ES.  12CF-71:  8 mos WCJ.  14CM-9 Ct 1: 8 mos WCJ  14CM-9 Ct 2:  6 mos WCJ. - Those 2 sentences concurrent with Ct 1 12CF-71 - all of jail sentences concurrent with 12CF-120 - with credit for 123 days of TS credit against those sentences.  
 

Those sentences are all concurrent to one another and are all concurrent to term of imprisonment in 12CF-120 and concurrent to 12CF-71 and 14CM-9.  
Terms of ES on each case:  Completion of AODA and any follow thru; Ab Sobriety; Bar Prohibition; No possession of any impairing substances unless valid RX; court costs inclusive of DNA for every charge and costs of $310 in purchase money related to the transactions of Cts 1-4 of INFO. Court costs be paid from up to 25% of inmate earnings, balance on ES.  No contact with N. Schubert.  No possession of any chemicals or materials used in the manufacture of synthetic cannabinoids.  As to sentence credit issue:  123 days sentence credit on the 3 SEHR cases.  Not entitled to sentence credit on Signature Bond cases.  Credit from arrest to Signature Bond - 10-21 to 10-30 or 9 days sentence credit against terms of imprisonment on Cts 1, 4 and 5.  Def is Eligible for CIP and also eligible for SARP.  

14CV-184:  As to Asset Forfeiture Case, State argues for order of forfeiture based upon Def's agreement.  Atty Goldin not appointed on CV case and offers proposal to not forfeit buy money and apply accordingly.  Court has no authority on application - statute clear on where money is to go once forfeited.  Def states he now wishes to continue to contest asset forfeiture case.  Hearing scheduled for that case - Defendant may appear via video for that hearing from the institution and will appear pro se.  Atty Goldin confirms receipt of correspondence from DA's office and that correspondence is returned directly to Def.  Def wishes to file with COC as an Answer.
